&gt; On Fri, May 10, 2002 at 01:01:15PM -0600, J. B. Rainsberger wrote:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; I believe assertEquals(o1, o2) essentially does this:
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; if( o1 == null ) {
&gt; &gt;     assertTrue(o1 == o2);
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt; else {
&gt; &gt;     assertTrue(o1.equals(o2));
&gt; &gt; }
&gt;
&gt; Yes, looking at the version in CVS it is this:
&gt;
&gt;   static public void assertEquals(String message, Object expected, Object
actual) {
&gt;     if (expected == null && actual == null)
&gt;       return;
&gt;     if (expected != null && expected.equals(actual))
&gt;       return;
&gt;     failNotEquals(message, expected, actual);
&gt;   }
&gt;
&gt; Some time ago on the German XP-list there was the suggestion, that
&gt; assertEquals might additionally check hashCode().  Thus changing the
&gt; second if-statement above to
&gt;
&gt;     if (expected != null && expected.equals(actual)) {
&gt;       if (expected.hashCode() != actual.hashCode())
&gt;         failDifferentHashcodes(message, expected, actual);
&gt;       else
&gt;         return;
&gt;     }
&gt;
&gt; Motivation: In the doc to Object.hashCode() it is stated:
&gt;
&gt;   # If two objects are equal according to the equals(Object)  method,
&gt;     then calling the hashCode method on each of the two objects must
&gt;     produce the same integer result.
&gt;
&gt; Earlier you wrote:
&gt; &gt; assertEquals() checks two objects for equality according to the equals()
&gt; &gt; method. It is not designed to test the validity of your equals() method;
&gt; &gt; quite the opposite, it relies on the correctness of your equals()
method.
&gt;
&gt; The change above to also check hashCode, would be a test of the
&gt; validity of equals(). But I consider it a feature, not a problem, even
&gt; though it is not a sufficient test.
&gt;
